Diagnosis
. Eye fused to orbit or mobile, pear-shaped, tapering towards small or almost undiscernible cornea; cornea pigmented or unpigmented; basal antennal article transversely rectangular, distinctly wider than long (
Fig. 6C–F
); epistome prominently sunken (
Fig. 13D
); anterolateral angle of merus of third maxilliped rounded (
Fig. 5B–I
); lateral edge of a5 some distance from cx4, 5, male opening coxo-sternal, penis long to very long with at least part of it exposed in channel between st7, st8; male abdomen does not protect penis when closed; large part of st8 visible even when male abdomen closed; female sterno-abdominal cavity relatively shallower, transversely broader, vulvae positioned on median parts of st6 (
Fig. 4B, D, F, H
).
